&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Exceptional Children-&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;The term &amp;nbsp;&amp;#39;exception stand for a separate and in many ways distinct category or class of children who have markedly e above a bridge are below average traits and characteristics which makes them fundamentally different from the general or average population of children.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;quot;An &lt;strong&gt;exceptional child &lt;/strong&gt;is he who deviates from the normal or average child in mental, physical and social characteristics to such an extent that he requires a modification of school practices or special education services to develop to his maximum capacity or supplementary instructions&amp;quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Gifted and Talented Children-&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;quot;The talented or gifted child shows consistently remarkable performance in any worthwhile line of endeavor. By receiving proper attention and opportunity for self-expression and development, he can contribute something remarkable to society&amp;rsquo;s welfare and humanity at large.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Mentally Retarded Children-&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;Mental Retardation Children with poor IQ are typically in the range of 70-75 or less. They have low adaptive behavior&amp;nbsp;or daily living skills, social skills, and communication skills. They are slower than their peers in acquiring life skills such as speech development or logic.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;Hence&lt;b&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gifted Children and Mentally Retardation children are exceptional children.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cognition and emotions are closely connected, with each influencing the other. Our thoughts and cognitive processes impact our emotions, and vice versa.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Emotions can affect our thinking, decision-making, and problem-solving abilities, while our cognitive processes can influence our emotional responses to particular situations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Our thoughts and feelings influence each other in a number of ways.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;For example, our emotions can influence how we perceive and interpret information, and our thoughts can influence how we feel emotionally.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, we can conclude that cognition and emotions are&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;interrelated to each other.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Psychological factors affecting learning&lt;/strong&gt; represent the internal, mental processes and states that influence how individuals acquire, process, and retain information.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These factors encompass a wide range of cognitive, emotional, and motivational aspects that can significantly impact a person&amp;#39;s ability to learn effectively.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A student&amp;#39;s interest is indeed a powerful psychological factor that can significantly impact their learning.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When students have a genuine interest in the subject matter, they&amp;#39;re eager to learn and soak up new knowledge, leading to deeper understanding and retention.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When students have a genuine interest in the subject matter, they&amp;#39;re more likely to connect the newly acquired knowledge to their existing understanding and real-world experiences.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, we can conclude that the psychological factor influencing Learning is the interest of students.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Motivation&lt;/strong&gt; plays a significant role in learning as it influences the level of engagement, effort, and persistence that students invest in the learning process.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;Intrinsic motivation&lt;/strong&gt; refers to engaging in an activity or learning for its inherent satisfaction, curiosity, or personal interest.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;When students have intrinsic motivation, they are driven by their internal desire to learn, explore, and understand the subject matter.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;They find enjoyment, fulfillment, and a sense of accomplishment in the learning process itself.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;nbsp;They are more likely to be actively engaged, show higher levels of effort, persist in the face of challenges, and demonstrate a deeper understanding and retention of the material.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, it is concluded&amp;nbsp;that&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Learning is effective when the students have intrinsic motivation.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Teachers&amp;#39; beliefs about success or failure generate through the trend they observe in the students. Teachers observe the students in the classroom and create a perception that they apply to all the students.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Teachers&amp;#39; beliefs influence learning through the methods adopted by the teachers and consequents affect the motivation of the students.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This influence is maximum in the disadvantaged group as they suffer the most impact of generalization while they are the most vulnerable and require special attention and different teaching process.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;A teacher can motivate students&amp;nbsp;and enh&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;ance learning by&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;setting realistic expectations&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;for them. The expectations should be&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;high enough&amp;nbsp;to motivate students but not so high which could lead to anxiety and frustration in students.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thus, it is concluded that&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;teacher expectancy influences children&amp;#39;s learning significantly &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;statement is correct regarding the above-mentioned context.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/hint-text-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Hint&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Teacher&amp;#39;s control over autonomy&lt;/strong&gt; does not influence learning and motivation, it has an impact on classroom discipline.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Teachers&amp;#39; encouragement to perform better than other students&lt;/strong&gt; is not the expectation set by the belief of the teachers, rather, the expectation that the weak students will continue to perform poorly.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Teachers do not expect all the students to pass, &lt;/strong&gt;they set a belief for&amp;nbsp;some particularly disadvantaged students that they may fail due to their poor classroom performance.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are many theories in psychology that are related to different schools of psychology such as&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;cognitive&lt;/span&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;humanistic&lt;/span&gt;,&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;behavioristic&lt;/span&gt;, etc.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;These theories are propounded by eminent psychologists to&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;provide a framework to understand different aspects of human behavior&lt;/span&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex; gap: 6px; align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/important-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Important Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700;&quot;&gt;Refer to the table to know important learning theories &amp;amp; their propounders:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;table border=&quot;1&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; style=&quot;width:350px;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;tbody&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Theory&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Propounder&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Main Idea&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Theory of Connectionism/S-R bond theory&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;E.L.Thorndike&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Learning is the result of&amp;nbsp;associations&amp;nbsp;forming between&amp;nbsp;stimulus and responses.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Theory of Operant Conditioning&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;B. F. Skinner&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;The theory implies the idea that&amp;nbsp;learning takes place through rewarding a certain behavior or withholding reward&amp;nbsp;for undesirable behavior.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Theory of classical conditioning&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;Ivan Pavlov&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;The theory emphasizes that&amp;nbsp;behavior is learned by a repetitive association&amp;nbsp;between the response and the stimulus.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gestalt theory of learning/Learning by Insight&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Wolfgang Kohler&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;The theory emphasizes that a&amp;nbsp;sudden solution to the problem&amp;nbsp;as insight doesn&amp;#39;t rely on behavior or observation.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Field theory&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;Kurt Lewin&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
			&lt;p&gt;It refers to the conceptual model of human behavior.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

			&lt;p&gt;It centered around the concept of relativism.&lt;br /&gt;
			According to this theory, nothing is perceivable or conceivable as a thing-in-itself; everything is perceived or conceived about other things.&lt;br /&gt;
			According to Lewin, our behavior is determined by our psychological person and our psychological environment.&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Hence, we can conclude that The propounder&amp;nbsp;of the&lt;strong&gt; Insight theory of Learning is Kohler.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;A method of teaching refers to the systematic and organized approach used by a teacher to deliver instructional content, facilitate learning, and achieve desired educational objectives in a structured manner.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Learning Objectives:&lt;/strong&gt; Choose methods aligned with specific educational goals and outcomes.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Student Characteristics:&lt;/strong&gt; Consider diverse student needs, including age, background, and learning styles.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Teacher Expertise:&lt;/strong&gt; Select methods that match the teacher&amp;#39;s mastery and strengths.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Classroom Environment:&lt;/strong&gt; Adapt methods based on class size, resources, and available technology.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Subject Matter:&lt;/strong&gt; Tailor methods to suit the nature of the content being taught.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Educational Technology:&lt;/strong&gt; Integrate technology tools that enhance the learning experience.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cultural Considerations:&lt;/strong&gt; Align teaching methods with cultural norms and values for better engagement.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Assessment Methods:&lt;/strong&gt; Ensure teaching methods align with the type of assessments used in the course.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Flexibility and Adaptability:&lt;/strong&gt; Be flexible, adapting methods based on ongoing feedback and evolving dynamics.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hence, all the above is the correct answer.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Slow learners often face challenges that can impact their self-esteem and motivation. They may feel frustrated or inadequate due to their difficulty in keeping up with their peers.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;Therefore, counseling, and guidance should prioritize addressing these emotional and psychological aspects.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fostering emotional support and building self-confidence&lt;/strong&gt; can help slow learners develop a more positive self-image and the belief that they can succeed with effort.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Enhance their motivation and overall well-being&lt;/strong&gt;, making it easier for them to engage in their academic pursuits and work towards improvement at their own pace.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The focus should not solely be on accelerating their learning, as this can add to their stress and anxiety, but rather on providing a&lt;strong&gt; supportive and nurturing environment for their holistic development.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Option 3 is the most appropriate choice for addressing the needs of slow learners.&amp;nbsp;&lt;span style=&quot;color: rgb(33, 37, 41);&quot;&gt;Providing emotional support and building self-confidence is particularly important for slow learners.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Micro-teaching, first proposed by&lt;strong&gt; Dwight W. Allen&lt;/strong&gt; and his colleagues at Stanford University &lt;strong&gt;in 1963&lt;/strong&gt;, is an instructional technique that is often used in teacher education.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It works by simplifying the complex task of teaching into manageable parts, to improve specific teaching skills.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Micro-teaching serves two main purposes:
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;To allow the teacher to learn and sharpen his/her teaching techniques under controlled conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;To provide the teacher with feedback from pupils and other teachers to improve his/her teaching techniques.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;In a micro-teaching session, the trainee teachers plan short lessons (usually 5-10 minutes) often with a very limited number of learners. The lessons focus on specific skills or objectives. After the lesson, they get feedback from their trainers and peers, which is used to improve their teaching strategies and techniques.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hence, we can conclude that option 1 is the correct answer.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
